  "prompt": "Where does the new nucleotides which result in formation of a DNA strand complimentary to the parent DNA in the end ,come from during DNA replication?",
  "response": "During DNA replication, new nucleotides come from the cell's nucleotide pool, which is derived from several sources:\n\n1. Cellular Nucleotide Synthesis:\n- Nucleotides are continuously synthesized within the cell\n- Two primary pathways:\n   a) De novo pathway (synthesizing nucleotides from scratch)\n   b) Salvage pathway (recycling existing nucleotide components)\n\n2. Specific Sources:\n- Nucleoside triphosphates (dATP, dTTP, dCTP, dGTP)\n- These are present in the cell's cytoplasm\n- Synthesized by enzymes like phosphoribosyltransferases\n- Produced during normal cellular metabolism\n\n3. Energy Requirement:\n- Nucleotide synthesis requires energy (ATP)\n- Occurs in the cell's cytoplasm and mitochondria\n\n4. Supply Mechanism:\n- Enzyme DNA polymerase selects and adds appropriate complementary nucleotides\n- Follows base-pairing rules (A-T, C-G)\n- Uses existing DNA strand as a template\n\n5. Continuous Supply:\n- Cell maintains a constant pool of nucleotides\n- Replenished through ongoing metabolic processes\n\nThese nucleotides are essential for creating the new complementary DNA strand during replication.",
